<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1058,981,1091]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1950" box="[462,586,981,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="1019" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[462,586,981,1002]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Pujoliclerus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
PIC was revised in 2014 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[858,995,981,1003]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013" pagination="727 - 756" refId="ref53564" refString="OPITZ W. (2014 d): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the checkered beetle genus Pujoliclerus PIC (Coleoptera: Cleridae: Peloniinae). - The Coleopteristss Bulletin 68 (4): 727 - 756." type="journal article" year="2014">OPITZ 2014d</bibRefCitation>
). This work included a key to species. 
<taxonomicName box="[485,709,1010,1032]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis box="[485,709,1010,1032]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Pujoliclerus convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens key to 
<emphasis box="[902,917,1011,1032]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[932,990,1011,1032]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">argus</emphasis>
OPITZ from which 
<taxonomicName box="[283,409,1040,1061]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexus">
<emphasis box="[283,409,1040,1061]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">P. convexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens differ by showing a terminal antennomere that is entirely black and a pronotum that is more convex and more transverse.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1059,1105,1407]" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 5.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,1105,1126]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,1105,1127]" captionStart="Figs 237-242" captionStartId="89.[151,191,1264,1286]" captionTargetBox="[153,1061,198,1249]" captionTargetId="figure@89.[153,1061,198,1249]" captionTargetPageId="89" captionText="Figs 237-242: Aedeagi; (237) Cregya arima; (238) C. biguttula; (239) C. vicosa; (240) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (241) Pelonium tayrona; (242) P. implacide." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746784" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746784/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 241</figureCitation>
. Color: Cranium bicolorous, clypeus and cranial venter yellow, frons and epicranium black; antenna black; prothorax bicolorous, venter and pronotal anterior angles yellow, pronotal disc mostly black; pterothorax and abdomen brown; legs mostly yellow, prothoracic tibiae and tarsi infuscated; elytra dark brown. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[159,238,1245,1267]" captionStart="Figs 1-27" captionStartId="70.[151,191,1302,1324]" captionTargetBox="[155,1057,207,1268]" captionTargetId="figure@70.[155,1058,207,1283]" captionTargetPageId="70" captionText="Figs 1-27: Antennae; (1) Aphelocerus nodus; (2) A. copanus; (3) A. magnipannus; (4) A. yoro; (5) A. sparicapillus; (6) A. tigra. (7) A. nolus; (8) A. ligulus; (9) Perilypus schusteri; (10) P. apunctus; (11) P. virgulatus; (12) P. izabal; (13) P. alpinus; (14) Cregya fuscomacula; (15) Phonius versus; (16) Pujoliclerus ariquemes; (17) Pelonium falcatum; (18) Pujoliclerus cnecostus; (19) P. trunculus. (20) P. sentus; (21) P. testudinatus; (22) P. catie; (23) P. flavidus; (24) P. convexus; (25) P. meloinus; (26) P. mexicoensis; (27) P. tuxtlas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746746" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746746/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
) capitate, most funicular antennomeres triangular, 6 
<superScript attach="left" box="[799,812,1241,1255]" fontSize="6" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">th</superScript>
antennomeres robustly expanded; capitular antennomeres 8 and 9 triangular, antennomere 10 ovoid; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 25/30). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[964,1051,1301,1323]" captionStart="Figs 134-152" captionStartId="77.[151,191,1476,1498]" captionTargetBox="[183,1049,204,1454]" captionTargetId="figure@77.[152,1060,199,1462]" captionTargetPageId="77" captionText="Figs 134-152: Pronota; (134) Pujoliclerus catie; (135) P. mexicoensis; (136) P. convexus; (137) P. testudinatus; (138) Madoniella selvanegra; (139) Cregya entrerios; (140) Pujoliclerus trunculus; (141) P. sentus; (142) P. meloinus; (143) Sicamus suprus; (144) Nepsudia guenda; (145) Nanoclerus fuscus; (146) Topainca pachacutii; (147) Eurycaulis anaxeis; (148) Kataspinula puebla; (149) Madoniella muralla; (150) M. nota; (151) M. acicula; (152) M. baja." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746760" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746760/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="1013">Fig. 136</figureCitation>
) transverse (PW/PL 70/65), disc coarsely punctate, lateral tubercles well developed; elytra sculptured with 9 striae of asetiferous punctures (EL/EW 220/65). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
